{
  "doc_id": "57555",
  "text": "Nowadays, digital mobile devices contain considerable amounts of valuable personal information, such as bank accounts and private emails [CITATION_1] ). These personal details make these devices the targets of various attacks. Hence, biological characteristics, such as fingerprints and irises [CITATION_2] , have been widely used as device passwords for further protecting the privacy information of users. This technique is called biometric verification. Recently, an increasing number of biometric verification based algorithms have emerged as a solution for continuous authentication on mobile devices. Many researchers have committed to designing active authentication algorithms based on face biometrics. For example, studies in [CITATION_3] , [CITATION_4] , [CITATION_5] detect faces through camera sensor images and further extract low-level features for the authentication of smartphone users.",
